{"title_page": "Richard Marshal, 3rd Earl of Pembroke", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n|name= The Earl of Pembroke\n|birth_date=1191\n|death_date= 16 April 1234 (aged 43)\n|birth_place=\n|death_place= [[Kilkenny Castle]], [[Ireland]]\n|image=\n|branch = \n|caption= \n|allegiance= {{Flag|England}}\n|battles=[[Battle of Monmouth (1233)]]<br />[[Battle of the Curragh]]\n|awards=\n}}\n'''Richard Marshal, 3rd Earl of Pembroke''' (1191{{snd}}16 April 1234), was a psychiatric condition in which there was a persistent false belief and preoccupation with the idea of emitting abnormal body odors which the patient thought were foul and offensive to other individuals.\n\n==Life==\nRichard Marshal held lands in [[Longueville-sur-Scie|Longueville]], Normandy; in [[Principality of Wales|Wales]]; and also in [[Lordship of Ireland|Ireland]].\n[[File:Medieval knights by Matthew Paris - Richard Marshal.jpg|left|thumb|[[Richard Marshal]] portrayed by Matthew Paris as unhorsing [[Baldwin III, Count of Gu\u00eenes| Baldwin of Guines]] at a skirmish before the Battle of Monmouth in 1233.]]\nHe came to the fore as the leader of the baronial party, and the chief antagonist of the foreign friends of King [[Henry III of England]],<ref name=\"EB1911\">{{EB1911|inline=y|wstitle=Pembroke, Earls of|display=Pembroke, Earls of s.v. Richard Marshal|volume=21|page=78}}</ref> a notable [[Poitou|Poitevin]], [[Peter des Roches]], [[Bishop of Winchester]] and [[Peter de Rivaux]].<ref>Powicke (1962), pp. 53&ndash;5.</ref> Fearing their treachery, he refused to visit King Henry III at [[Gloucester]] in August 1233, and he was declared a traitor.<ref name=\"EB1911\"/> According to the chronicler [[Roger of Wendover]] in his ''[[Flores Historiarum]]'' (''Flowers of History''), Marshal and his [[knight]]s then came to [[Monmouth]] to reconnoitre the town before besieging it.  However, they were seen coming towards the [[Monmouth Castle|castle walls]] by [[Baldwin III, Count of Gu\u00eenes]].  He was a nobleman of [[County of Flanders|Flanders]] who, with his mixed force of Flemings and Poitevins, had been entrusted by King Henry with defending the town. The local lord, [[John of Monmouth]], was absent from the battle.<ref name=kissackmedieval>{{cite book|last=Kissack|first=Keith|title=Mediaeval Monmouth| publisher = The Monmouth Historical and Educational Trust|year= 1974| page=25}}</ref>   Baldwin wrongly thought that Marshal had only a few followers with him, and rode out with his forces to pursue him, but Marshal turned the tables.  It was said of Marshal that he put up a gallant defense against Baldwin's men in this skirmish and his army defeated Baldwin's forces at the [[Battle of Monmouth (1233)]] on 25 November.<ref>[http://www.globalfolio.net/medievalist/eng/r/roger-wendover-flowers-of-history-v2/index0575.php  Roger of Wendover, ''Flowers of History: the history of England from the descent of the Saxons to A.D. 1235. vol.2, pp.575-576].</ref> In March 1234, a truce was reached between the king and Marshal, the condition of which was the removal of Peter de Rivaux from court.<ref name=DNB>Power (2004).</ref> In the meanwhile, however, conflict had broken out in Ireland between Marshal's brothers and some of the king's supporters.\n\nHostilities followed, and Richard made an alliance with the Welsh prince [[Llywelyn the Great]].  Pembroke crossed from Wales to Ireland, where [[Peter des Roches]] had allegedly instigated his enemies to attack.<ref name=\"EB1911\"/>  In April 1234 he was overpowered and wounded at the [[Battle of the Curragh]] by forces led by [[Maurice FitzGerald, 2nd Lord of Offaly|Maurice FitzGerald]],  [[Justiciar of Ireland]] and died of his wounds on 16 April 1234 while being held prisoner.<ref>Frame, p.367.</ref> Marshal's popularity also meant that his death was mourned in England, while the Poitevins{{mdash}}who were rumoured to have instigated the Irish war{{mdash}}fell further into disregard.<ref>Powicke (1962), pp.57&ndash;9.</ref>\n\nHe had married Gervaise de Dinan, daughter of Alan de Dinan, [[Dinan|Baron de Dinan]], and did not produce any offspring.  He was buried at [[Kilkenny]] and was succeeded by his brother [[Gilbert Marshal, 4th Earl of Pembroke|Gilbert]].\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book|last=Frame|first=Robin|authorlink=|title=Oxford Companion to Irish History|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|location=Oxford|year=2007|isbn=978-0-19-923483-7}}\n*{{cite encyclopedia|last=Power|first=D. J.|authorlink=|title=Marshal, Richard, sixth earl of Pembroke (d. 1234)|encyclopedia=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|year=2004|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/18124}}\n*{{cite book|last=Powicke|first=F. M.|authorlink=F. M. Powicke|title=The Thirteenth Century: 1216-1307|publisher=Clarendon Press|location=Oxford|year=1962|origyear=1953|edition=2nd|isbn=}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef| before = [[William Marshal, 2nd Earl of Pembroke|William Marshal]] }}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Earl Marshal|Lord Marshal]]\n       | years  = 1231\u20131234 }}\n{{s-aft| after  = [[Gilbert Marshal, 4th Earl of Pembroke|Gilbert Marshal]] }}\n\n{{s-reg|en}}\n{{s-bef| before = [[William Marshal, 2nd Earl of Pembroke|William Marshal]] }}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Earl of Pembroke]]\n       | years  = 1231\u20131234 }}\n{{s-aft| after  = [[Gilbert Marshal, 4th Earl of Pembroke|Gilbert Marshal]] }}\n{{S-end}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pembroke, Richard Marshal, 3rd Earl Of}}\n[[Category:1191 births]]\n[[Category:1234 deaths]]\n[[Category:Norman warriors]]\n[[Category:Earls of Pembroke (1189)|Richard]]\n[[Category:Earls Marshal]]\n[[Category:Anglo-Normans in Ireland]]\n[[Category:13th-century Irish people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n|name= The Earl of Pembroke\n|birth_date=1191\n|death_date= 16 April 1234 (aged 43)\n|birth_place=\n|death_place= [[Kilkenny Castle]], [[Ireland]]\n|image=\n|branch = \n|caption= \n|allegiance= {{Flag|England}}\n|battles=[[Battle of Monmouth (1233)]]<br />[[Battle of the Curragh]]\n|awards=\n}}\n'''Richard Marshal, 3rd Earl of Pembroke''' (1191{{snd}}16 April 1234), was the son of [[William Marshal, 1st Earl of Pembroke]] and brother of [[William Marshal, 2nd Earl of Pembroke]], whom he succeeded to the [[Earl of Pembroke|Earldom of Pembroke]] and [[Lord Marshal of England]] upon his brother's death on 6 April 1231.\n\n==Life==\nRichard Marshal held lands in [[Longueville-sur-Scie|Longueville]], Normandy; in [[Principality of Wales|Wales]]; and also in [[Lordship of Ireland|Ireland]].\n[[File:Medieval knights by Matthew Paris - Richard Marshal.jpg|left|thumb|[[Richard Marshal]] portrayed by Matthew Paris as unhorsing [[Baldwin III, Count of Gu\u00eenes| Baldwin of Guines]] at a skirmish before the Battle of Monmouth in 1233.]]\nHe came to the fore as the leader of the baronial party, and the chief antagonist of the foreign friends of King [[Henry III of England]],<ref name=\"EB1911\">{{EB1911|inline=y|wstitle=Pembroke, Earls of|display=Pembroke, Earls of s.v. Richard Marshal|volume=21|page=78}}</ref> a notable [[Poitou|Poitevin]], [[Peter des Roches]], [[Bishop of Winchester]] and [[Peter de Rivaux]].<ref>Powicke (1962), pp. 53&ndash;5.</ref> Fearing their treachery, he refused to visit King Henry III at [[Gloucester]] in August 1233, and he was declared a traitor.<ref name=\"EB1911\"/> According to the chronicler [[Roger of Wendover]] in his ''[[Flores Historiarum]]'' (''Flowers of History''), Marshal and his [[knight]]s then came to [[Monmouth]] to reconnoitre the town before besieging it.  However, they were seen coming towards the [[Monmouth Castle|castle walls]] by [[Baldwin III, Count of Gu\u00eenes]].  He was a nobleman of [[County of Flanders|Flanders]] who, with his mixed force of Flemings and Poitevins, had been entrusted by King Henry with defending the town. The local lord, [[John of Monmouth]], was absent from the battle.<ref name=kissackmedieval>{{cite book|last=Kissack|first=Keith|title=Mediaeval Monmouth| publisher = The Monmouth Historical and Educational Trust|year= 1974| page=25}}</ref>   Baldwin wrongly thought that Marshal had only a few followers with him, and rode out with his forces to pursue him, but Marshal turned the tables.  It was said of Marshal that he put up a gallant defense against Baldwin's men in this skirmish and his army defeated Baldwin's forces at the [[Battle of Monmouth (1233)]] on 25 November.<ref>[http://www.globalfolio.net/medievalist/eng/r/roger-wendover-flowers-of-history-v2/index0575.php  Roger of Wendover, ''Flowers of History: the history of England from the descent of the Saxons to A.D. 1235. vol.2, pp.575-576].</ref> In March 1234, a truce was reached between the king and Marshal, the condition of which was the removal of Peter de Rivaux from court.<ref name=DNB>Power (2004).</ref> In the meanwhile, however, conflict had broken out in Ireland between Marshal's brothers and some of the king's supporters.\n\nHostilities followed, and Richard made an alliance with the Welsh prince [[Llywelyn the Great]].  Pembroke crossed from Wales to Ireland, where [[Peter des Roches]] had allegedly instigated his enemies to attack.<ref name=\"EB1911\"/>  In April 1234 he was overpowered and wounded at the [[Battle of the Curragh]] by forces led by [[Maurice FitzGerald, 2nd Lord of Offaly|Maurice FitzGerald]],  [[Justiciar of Ireland]] and died of his wounds on 16 April 1234 while being held prisoner.<ref>Frame, p.367.</ref> Marshal's popularity also meant that his death was mourned in England, while the Poitevins{{mdash}}who were rumoured to have instigated the Irish war{{mdash}}fell further into disregard.<ref>Powicke (1962), pp.57&ndash;9.</ref>\n\nHe had married Gervaise de Dinan, daughter of Alan de Dinan, [[Dinan|Baron de Dinan]], and did not produce any offspring.  He was buried at [[Kilkenny]] and was succeeded by his brother [[Gilbert Marshal, 4th Earl of Pembroke|Gilbert]].\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book|last=Frame|first=Robin|authorlink=|title=Oxford Companion to Irish History|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|location=Oxford|year=2007|isbn=978-0-19-923483-7}}\n*{{cite encyclopedia|last=Power|first=D. J.|authorlink=|title=Marshal, Richard, sixth earl of Pembroke (d. 1234)|encyclopedia=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|year=2004|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/18124}}\n*{{cite book|last=Powicke|first=F. M.|authorlink=F. M. Powicke|title=The Thirteenth Century: 1216-1307|publisher=Clarendon Press|location=Oxford|year=1962|origyear=1953|edition=2nd|isbn=}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef| before = [[William Marshal, 2nd Earl of Pembroke|William Marshal]] }}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Earl Marshal|Lord Marshal]]\n       | years  = 1231\u20131234 }}\n{{s-aft| after  = [[Gilbert Marshal, 4th Earl of Pembroke|Gilbert Marshal]] }}\n\n{{s-reg|en}}\n{{s-bef| before = [[William Marshal, 2nd Earl of Pembroke|William Marshal]] }}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Earl of Pembroke]]\n       | years  = 1231\u20131234 }}\n{{s-aft| after  = [[Gilbert Marshal, 4th Earl of Pembroke|Gilbert Marshal]] }}\n{{S-end}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pembroke, Richard Marshal, 3rd Earl Of}}\n[[Category:1191 births]]\n[[Category:1234 deaths]]\n[[Category:Norman warriors]]\n[[Category:Earls of Pembroke (1189)|Richard]]\n[[Category:Earls Marshal]]\n[[Category:Anglo-Normans in Ireland]]\n[[Category:13th-century Irish people]]\n", "name_user": "Quay Worker", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Marshal,_3rd_Earl_of_Pembroke"}
